Some of the paintings in Liz Tran’s current exhibition are reprised from a mid-2021 one, but they have a new venue and a new centerpiece. Although both shows were organized by Morton Fine Art, “Matriarchs and Daughters Dream Oceans of Braille” is installed at Homme, where the abstract pictures flank a 16-foot-long vertical banner that drapes down a wall and pools on the floor. Made in collaboration with Tran’s mother, and incorporating part of a grandmother’s tablecloth, the piece inspired the show’s title, which refers to intergenerational connections and the tactile nature of fabric work.

Of the other pieces, only three are circular in format, but all feature copious spheres, points and rounded blotches. Tran applies hot-colored forms in various media, often densely overlapped on cream-hued backdrops. Drips are indulged, or even encouraged, and rings of painted dots often trace the circumferences of larger orbs.
While the Seattle artist’s color schemes have a floral quality, the abundance of twinkling marks suggests star maps. That affinity is acknowledged by the title of one series excerpted here, “Cosmic Circle,” but the initial inspiration for Tran’s compositional mode is actually the Rorschach inkblot. The vast, profuse expanses in these paintings represent the psychological as much as the interstellar.
Liz Tran: Matriarchs and Daughters Dream Oceans of Braille Through Jan. 6 at Morton Fine Art at Homme, 2000 L St. NW. Open by appointment.

Book you appointment to view “Salon Style : Summer Small Works” on view through September 2, 2023.

Morton Fine Art is pleased to present Salon Style: Summer Small Works, an intimate salon-style group exhibition of small-scale works. Ranging in materials and techniques— collage, paintings and drawings on paper, canvas or mixed media—the exhibition nests a variety of forms, textures, charged considerations of figuration and abstraction and approaches to depth and composition. Featuring work from the gallery’s artists-partners, the exhibition’s represented artists include Osi Audu, Michael Andrew Booker, Lisa Myers Bulmash, Hannelie Coetzee, Rosemary Feit Covey, Katherine Hattam, Astrid Kohler, Hiromitsu Kuroo, Choichun Leung, Eto Otitigbe, Prina Shah, Vonn Cummings Sumner, Liz Tran and Jenny Wu. Including more than 40 works measuring 16” and smaller,  Salon Style: Summer Small Works is an accessible and intimately immense exhibit.
 
Salon Style: Summer Small Works will be on view from July 29 to September 2, 2023 at Morton Fine Art’s Washington, D.C. location (52 O St NW #302).

I just spent the most beautiful weekend in Tieton, a small town that sits across the mountains from Seattle in Yakima county. It was an honor to jury the @tietonarts 10 x 10 exhibition, with 500+ submissions and 200 works shown. It’s worth the trek from Seattle, I promise!
Many thanks to the all of the artists who took the time to submit work and thank you to the fantastic @artbyrosiesaldana for facilitating. She is doing big things for the artist community in and around Tieton.
In addition, my dear friend @janicelv52 was giving away free art supplies from The Portal Project. If you would like to donate supplies, please dm me and I will put you in contact with her. They will be put to good use! 
I’d also like to thank the incredible artist #Trimpin for giving my mom and I a tour of his new home and studio in Tieton. The player pianos in this post are his. I’ve always admired the playfulness of his practice.
Last but not least, thank you to @ed_marquand for his hospitality and dedication to the arts and @the_nido for putting us up!

Varying her compositions from symmetrical renderings–like a Rorschach print–to others more liberally abstracted, Tran’s works challenge the notion of a correct way to view art. Like the well-known psychological test, Tran’s art performs an introspective function in which the viewer’s interpretation is self-reflexive and can facilitate self-knowledge.

The Moonium Luminis, commonly known as the “Lunaflora,” is a species of flowering plant that captivates the imagination with its ethereal beauty and unique botanical characteristics. Belonging to the genus Moonium within the family Lunaceae, this captivating blossom is colloquially referred to as the “Moon Flower” due to its remarkable luminescent properties.

Moonium Luminis exhibits an intricate floral structure, characterized by delicately arranged petals that subtly reflect the pale glow of moonlight. The plant’s Latin name, “luminis,” alludes to its luminous quality, emphasizing the enchanting radiance emitted by its petals during the night. This species is designed with bio-luminescent pigments, allowing it to absorb sunlight during the day and emit a soft, celestial glow after sunset.

Within the scientific community, Moonium luminis has garnered interest for its potential applications in the field of bioillumination research. The flower’s unique adaptation to harness and store solar energy for nocturnal display sparks curiosity among botanists and materials scientists alike. Its petals contain hypothetical light-absorbing compounds and photonic structures that simulate the principles of solar energy conversion and emission, inspiring novel avenues for biomimetic technologies.

Despite its fictitious nature, the Moon Flower serves as a compelling concept, illustrating the intersection of botanical wonder and scientific curiosity. The hypothetical Moonium luminis remains a symbol of the unexplored realms of nature, encouraging scientific inquiry and sparking the imagination of those fascinated by the mysteries of the plant kingdom.

Genus: Noctiflora
Noctiflora, a fascinating genus of botanical specimens, exhibits a unique and enchanting characteristic in the plant kingdom. Distinguished by their exclusive blooming pattern at dusk, these flowers have evolved specialized adaptations to harness the ephemeral twilight hours for optimal pollination and reproduction.
Belonging to the family Nyctaginaceae, Noctiflora species have been identified across various geographical regions, showcasing the adaptability of this floral phenomenon. Notable members of this genus include Noctiflora lumina, Noctiflora crepusculum, and Noctiflora vesperalis, each manifesting distinct morphological features and ecological preferences.
The intricate biological mechanisms governing the nocturnal blooming of Noctiflora involve a finely tuned internal circadian rhythm synchronized with the diminishing light levels at dusk. Photoreceptors within their petals respond to specific wavelengths of light, triggering a cascade of molecular events that culminate in the unfolding of delicate, fragrant blossoms as the sun sets.
The reproductive strategy of Noctiflora hinges on attracting crepuscular pollinators, such as moths and nocturnal insects, which are essential for ensuring successful fertilization. The flowers emit subtle yet alluring fragrances and produce nectar-rich reservoirs to entice their nocturnal counterparts, fostering a symbiotic relationship that perpetuates the survival and genetic diversity of the genus.
Noctiflora not only exemplifies the wonders of botanical adaptation but also provides a captivating subject for further investigation into the molecular and ecological intricacies underlying their unique flowering behavior. As scientific exploration advances, the genus Noctiflora stands as a testament to the marvels of nature’s precision and the intricate dance between flora and fauna in the twilight hours.

Hortus Nocturnalis Psycotropica:

The Hortus Nocturnalis Psycotropica, an extraordinary botanical enclave, represents a synthesis of botanical richness and botanical surrealism, designed to captivate the senses under the veil of darkness. In this nocturnal sanctuary, an array of unique flora, curated for both medicinal and hallucinogenic properties, beckons exploration and contemplation.

Dominating the landscape is the imposing Luminis Nocturnalis, an otherworldly tree adorned with phosphorescent foliage that casts an otherworldly glow upon the garden. Its bark, named Cortex Phantasmagoricus, contains compounds with therapeutic qualities and subtle psychedelic undertones, offering a sensory experience that transcends the mundane.

Among the enchanting blooms, the Nyctopetala Divinorum emerges as a star attraction, its radiant petals releasing a fragrance that blends medicinal notes with the faintest whiff of the surreal. This hybrid marvel, a testament to botanical alchemy, harbors compounds known for their therapeutic efficacy and subtle psychotropic effects.

Nestled beneath the Nyctopetala Divinorum, the Solanum Hypnoticum flourishes, boasting potent alkaloids that induce a dreamlike state when carefully prepared. Its velvety leaves and iridescent flowers pay homage to the mesmerizing allure of the night, while its pharmacological potential invites contemplation and study.
